Factors affecting our health: Data Analysis with Logistic Regression

Yuean Wang





1 Intro



What affects our health? Apart from obvious answers such as weight, age, BMI, could there be other factors that we normally wouldn’t expect to affect our health deeply? And also among these factors that can influence our health, what are the most significant factors and how are they going to influence our health?

To answer these questions, we will be using Logistic Regression Model to analyze the relationships between different influencer and our health. And to optimize our model, we will be using cross-validation as well as decision tree pruning to further improve our prediction.

2 Data Handling

2.1 Collecting data



The original dataset was collected by the US National Health and Nutrition Examination Study in 2011. See Here for more detailed information.

Since we would like to predict on the variable HealthGen, a variable that represents the health of the participant in general, we will only select 17 variables from the original data set: Gender,Age,Race1,Education,MaritalStatus,HHIncome,BMI_WHO,HealthGen,Depressed, SleepTrouble,PhysActiveDays,TVHrsDay,CompHrsDay,AlcoholYear,SmokeNow,RegularMarij, SexOrientation

For our analysis, we only select entries from the year 2011 and from participants who’s age is within 18 and 59.

First we need to ensure that there aren’t any missing value in the column HealthGen, as it is our predictor.

Then by looking at the number of invalid entries, we decided to drop the variables PhysActiveDays, SmokeNow and AlcoholYear, as they each have over 500 invalid values. With these three variables included in the dataset, we would be removing more data entries later on.

Lastly we proceed to omit any rows that contains missing value, now we are left with a dataset with 2,118 rows and 14 columns 

# Drop rows with missing outcomes (HealthGenNum)
dat = dat[complete.cases(dat[, 'HealthGen']),]

3 Building Model



In this study we will be the step-wise selection procedure.

3.1 Prescreening



Notice that HealthGen is categorized into five response, Excellent, Vgood, Good, Fair, and Poor. In order to simplify the analysis process and to conduct logistics regression, we will be convert HealthGen into a binary variable, Excellent/Vgood VS Good/Fair/Poor, with 1 representing Excellent/Vgood.

par(mfrow=c(1,2))

  theme_minimal()

3.2 Forward Selection



In this step, we add each of the variable to the null model and test it against the null model. We record their respective p values and add variables with p value < 0.1 to the model.

##### UNIVARIATE SCREENING #####
p_value <- rep(NA, length(factors))

fit0 = glm(HealthGenNum~1, family=binomial(), data=dat)

#loop through each of the element and test the univariate model
for (i in 1:length(factors)) {
  factor = factors[i]
  fit1 = glm(as.formula(paste("HealthGenNum~", paste(factor))), family=binomial(), 
             data=dat)
  
  p_value[[i]] <- anova(fit0, fit1, test="LRT")$"Pr(>Chi)"[2]
}

uni_df <- data.frame(factors,p_value)

# Plot
ggplot(uni_df, aes(x=factors, y=p_value)) + geom_hline(yintercept=0.1,color="red",size =0.6,alpha=0.8) +
  geom_point(size=2.5,shape=1) + 
  geom_segment(aes(x=factors, xend=factors, 
                   y=0, yend=p_value))+
  labs(title="P Value Chart", caption="source: dat") + 
  theme_bw() + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle=65, vjust=0.6))

3.3 Backwards Elimination:



After adding all the significant variables to the model, we then perform backwards elimination on the multivariate mode. We take one variable out each time and test it against the full model. Again, we record their p value respectively. We use a 0.05 cut off for eliminating non-significant variables.

##### BACKWARDS SELECTION #####

#Multivariate model with all significant variable

4 Interaction terms



Now we finished analyzing the final model, but could there be any factors we are missing on? What if when two factors combined together they can also significantly influence our result? To answer this question, we will be looking at interaction terms, namely the interaction between any two factors.

Among the 8 final variables, there are unique 28 pairwise interaction terms. We compare A+B with A+B+A*B for each pair and using forward selection with a significance level of 0.01 to filter our result.

### Generate interaction terms
final_factors <- c("Age", "Race1", "BMI_WHO_30_Plus", "Education", "HHIncome", "Depressed", "SleepTrouble", "TVHrsDay_More_4_Hrs")

len_ff = length(final_factors)
interaction_p_value <- rep(NA, len_ff*(len_ff-1)*0.5)
interaction_factors <- character()

count <- 0
for (i in 1:(len_ff-1)) {
  for (j in (i+1):len_ff){
    
    #model: A+B
    interaction <- c(final_factors[i],final_factors[j])
    final_fit0<- glm(as.formula(paste("HealthGenNum~",paste(interaction,collapse="+"))),
                family=binomial(),data=dat)
    
    #model: A+B+A*B
    interaction_factors <- c(interaction_factors, paste(interaction, collapse="*"))
  
    count <- count+1
    final_temp <- c(interaction,interaction_factors[count])
    final_fit1 <- glm(as.formula(paste("HealthGenNum~", paste(final_temp, collapse="+"))),
                           family=binomial(),data=dat)

    interaction_p_value[[count]] <- anova(final_fit0,final_fit1,test ="LRT")$"Pr(>Chi)"[2]

  }
}

interaction_df <- data.frame(interaction_factors,interaction_p_value)

# Plot
ggplot(interaction_df, aes(x=interaction_factors, y=interaction_p_value)) +   
  geom_hline(yintercept=0.01,color="red",size =0.6,alpha=0.8) +
  geom_segment(aes(x=interaction_factors, xend=interaction_factors, 
                   y=0, yend=interaction_p_value))+

5 Model evaluation with ROC, AUC, and CV



Now that we have our final model with and without interaction terms, we would like to assess these two models. We will be looking at r-squared, ROC/AUC and cross-validation error.

5.1 R-squared



R-squared is the proportion of the variance in the dependent variable that is predictable from the independent variable(s). (Wiki)

# Compute generalized r^2
all_fit_rsq = 1-exp(logLik(final_fit)/nrow(dat))
print("R-squared for final model: ")
## [1] "R-squared for final model: "
all_fit_rsq
## 'log Lik.' 0.4354599 (df=26)
all_fit_rsq_int = 1-exp(logLik(final_fit_int)/nrow(dat))
print("R-squared for final model with interaction: ")
## [1] "R-squared for final model with interaction: "
all_fit_rsq_int
## 'log Lik.' 0.3963611 (df=155)



According to the R-squared values, the final model can explain more of the variance than the model with interactions. However, both of them only explain about 40% of the variance. One reasons might be that since we transform the HealthGen variable to a binary variable, there’s an inevitable loss in information. Also another explanation would be that we are still missing some important factors in our dataset.

5.2 ROC/AUC



A receiver operating characteristic curve, or ROC curve, is a graphical plot that illustrates the diagnostic ability of a binary classifier system as its discrimination threshold is varied.(Wiki).ROC curves are used to show in a graphical way to trade offs between sensitivity (true positives) and (1-specificity)(false positives).

The best possible prediction method would yield a point in the upper left corner or coordinate (0,1) of the ROC space, representing 100% sensitivity (no false negatives) and 100% specificity (no false positives). The (0,1) point is also called a perfect classification. A random guess would give a point along a diagonal line (the so-called line of no-discrimination) from the left bottom to the top right corners (regardless of the positive and negative base rates).(Wiki,15)

The area under the the ROC curve, AUC gives us the idea of how beneficial the model is. The greater area the AUC is, the more useful the test is.

plot.roc(dat$HealthGenNum, predict(final_fit, type = "response"),print.auc=TRUE, col="blue")
plot.roc(dat$HealthGenNum, predict(final_fit_int, type = "response"),print.auc=TRUE,col="red",
     print.auc.y=0.4,add=TRUE)



Here the blue line represents the ROC curve for the final model, and the red line represents for the final model with interaction terms.

According to the plot, final model with interaction terms actually gives us a better prediction of the outcome. And to further investigate on this idea, we will employ cross-validation on the two models.

5.3 Cross-validation



. Validation involves splitting the dataset into training and testing two parts. We used the training set to train our model and the testing set to evaluate our model with unseen data. This can help preventing the model from over-fitting with the data. Cross-validation is using different splitting of the training/test set every time of the same dataset to do the validation process.

k = 10
set.seed(123)
folds<-cvFolds(nrow(dat), K=k)
auc = numeric(length=k)
auc_int = numeric(length=k)
for(i in 1:k) {
  mov.train = dat[folds$subsets[folds$which !=i],]
  mov.test = dat[folds$subsets[folds$which == i],]
  final_fit = glm(as.formula(paste("HealthGenNum~", paste(factors, collapse="+"))), family=binomial(), data=mov.train)
  final_fit_int = glm(as.formula(paste("HealthGenNum~", paste(final_w_int, collapse="+"))), family=binomial(), data=mov.train)
  auc[i]=auc(mov.test$HealthGenNum, predict(final_fit, newdata = mov.test,type="response"))
  auc_int[i]=auc(mov.test$HealthGenNum, predict(final_fit_int, newdata = mov.test,type="response"))
}


print("Auc for the final model:")
## [1] "Auc for the final model:"
summary(auc)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##  0.7082  0.7407  0.7655  0.7586  0.7753  0.7981
print("Average auc for the final model with interactions:")
## [1] "Average auc for the final model with interactions:"
summary(auc_int)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##  0.7096  0.7404  0.7555  0.7572  0.7810  0.7874

We can see that the interaction model are not exactly more accurate than the final model. Indeed, the two model performs similarly for an average auc of 75.8% throughout 10 folds cross-validation.

We conclude that the two models are not statistical significantly different from each other.

6.1 Tree Pruning



Pruning is a data compression technique in machine learning and search algorithms that reduces the size of decision trees by removing sections of the tree that are non-critical and redundant to classify instances. Pruning reduces the complexity of the final classifier, and hence improves predictive accuracy by the reduction of over-fitting. (Wiki)



In this study we will be comparing two methods of pruning. There are usually two approaches to select the optimal cp (complexity parameter)

  • Select the cp which provides the smallest xerror, if there are multiple cp’s providing the smallest xerror, choose the largest one among them.

  • Select the largest cp such that xerror<min(error)+xstd, this is suggested in help(plotcp).

#Prune Approach 1
cp1=multi_fit_tree$cptable[which.min(multi_fit_tree$cptable[,"xerror"]),"CP"]
multi_fit_prune1=prune(multi_fit_tree, cp=cp1)

plot(multi_fit_prune1, uniform=TRUE, main="Prune Tree 1 w/n")
text(multi_fit_prune1, srt=10, pretty=0, use.n=TRUE,  all=TRUE)

#Prune Approach 2
cp2=multi_fit_tree$cptable[min(which(multi_fit_tree$cptable[,"xerror"]<=min(multi_fit_tree$cptable[,"xerror"])+multi_fit_tree$cptable[,"xstd"])),"CP"]
multi_fit_prune2=prune(multi_fit_tree, cp=cp2)

plot(multi_fit_prune2, uniform=TRUE, main="Prune Tree 2 w/n")
text(multi_fit_prune2, srt=10, pretty=0, all=TRUE, use.n=TRUE)

6.2 Cross-validation



Again we want to make sure that the difference are not just by chance. We are running a 10 folds cross-validation to verify our conclusion.

##Testing Error repeated 10 times
err_test3=numeric()
err_test4=numeric()
err_test_guess=numeric()
for (b in 1:10){
  #split dataset
  trainT=sample.int(nrow(tree_dat),floor(nrow(tree_dat)*0.9))
  testT=(1:nrow(tree_dat))[-trainT]
  #build tree and prune w/ approach 1
  multi_fitT=rpart(as.formula(paste("HealthGenNum~",paste(factors_tree,collapse="+"))), data=tree_dat, subset=trainT)
  cp3=multi_fitT$cptable[which.min(multi_fitT$cptable[,"xerror"]),"CP"]
  multi_fit_prune3=prune(multi_fitT, cp=cp3)
  #calculate test error
  predict_table3=table(predict(multi_fit_prune3,newdata=tree_dat[testT,],type="class"),tree_dat$HealthGenNum[testT])
  err_test3[b]=1-sum(diag(predict_table3))/sum(predict_table3) 
  #prune with approach 2
  cp4=multi_fitT$cptable[min(which(multi_fitT$cptable[,"xerror"]<=min(multi_fitT$cptable[,"xerror"])+multi_fitT$cptable[,"xstd"])),"CP"]
  multi_fit_prune4=prune(multi_fitT, cp=cp4)
  #calculate test error
  predict_table4=table(predict(multi_fit_prune4,newdata=tree_dat[testT,],type="class"),tree_dat$HealthGenNum[testT])
  err_test4[b]=1-sum(diag(predict_table4))/sum(predict_table4)  
  
  err_test_guess[b]=min(prop.table(table(tree_dat$HealthGenNum[testT]))) 
}
print("Average Relative Error for Approach 1: ")
## [1] "Average Relative Error for Approach 1: "
mean(err_test3)/mean(err_test_guess) 
## [1] 0.7955272
print("Average Relative Error for Approach 2: ")
## [1] "Average Relative Error for Approach 2: "
mean(err_test4)/mean(err_test_guess) 
## [1] 0.8093717



The two models perform similarly after 10 tests. So essentially they achieve the same results.

Notice that even after pruning, the relative error compared to majority voting is still relative high for both our model. This might be because we did not include any of the interaction terms.

7 Conclusion



In conclusion, by running Logistic Regression on our model, we had a few discoveries.

  • A bad lifestyle is detrimental to our health. BMI over 30, watching TV for more than 4 hours.day, depression, sleeping troubles are almost equivalent to having a fairer health condition.

  • On the contrary, factors leading to a good health condition are not so clear. Our model suggest a combination of higher education level, higher household income might lead to a healthier environments, but they are not as deciding as the bad lifestyles.

  • From these two observation, we can conclude that to achieve better health, the most important thing to do is to live a good lifestyle.

7.1 Limitations to Analysis



  • Since we have a large number of variables for our model, we had to use extreme p-value conditions (<0.01) to narrow down the number of variables. However, one of the possible trade-offs is that our model might become over-fitting.

  • At the beginning of screening, we decided to transform three of the variables into binary variables due to multiple of levels. Although by doing so we are forcing the model to focusing on more important categories, we are also suffering from the loss of information due to the process.
